ike Swift to little known manuscript sources and prints. As the book emphasises, satire was a frame of reference for well-known authors and artists ranging from Milton to Bernini and Goya. It was moreover a broad European phenomenon: while the book focuses on English satire, it also considers France, Italy, The Netherlands and Spain, and discusses how satirical texts and artwork could move between countries and languages. In its wide sweep across time and formats, Changing satire brings out the importance that satire had as a transgressor of borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEuropean literaturey17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSatirexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean satire.  aearly modern satire.  aformal verse satire.  agenre history.  agraphic satire.  aintermediality.  apolitical satire.  asatire and theatre.  asocial satire.  athe history of satire.1 aBricker, Andrew Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrandjouan, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacNeill, Máire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarx, Lizzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoul, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurgia, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNolan, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOnelli, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 